We are intrigued by the somewhat whimsical plea from the Western Cape MEC for economic opportunities, Alan Winde, on the effects of the drought, which, at one juncture, threatened to edge this country towards near dust bowl status. The enterprising Winde urged everyone to do their bit and drink wine. On the face of it, this suggestion made in jest we trust, to delegates at the inaugural African Agribusiness indaba seems like a fine idea. It falls perfectly in line with the thinking of French chemist and microbiologist Louis Pasteur, who unveiled the principles of vaccination, microbial fermentation and pasteurisation, and said: Wine is the most healthful and most hygienic of beverages. It should be added that viniculture and the production of fine wines raises an important and, dare we say, welcome toast at the mixed table of the South African economy. While water may be vital to sustaining life, a glass of the Cape s finest certainly makes that existence more tolerable and allows us to relax, and talk more easily on what is troubling us. For did Pliny the Elder, an author, naturalist and natural philosopher, as well as naval and army commander of the early Roman Empire, encapsulate it perfectly by sagely noting: In wine, there s truth. For more news your way, follow The Citizen on Facebook and Twitter.